  section.timeline 
    h2 A Brief History of Matt...
    hr
    ul 
      li 
        div 
          time September 1, 2013 
          p I wrote my first line of code in Computer Science 101.
          code print("Hello, world!")
          p I thought I was the next Mark Zuckerberg (Im still hoping I might have been right!)
          p That was the moment my passion for programming started, and I didn't stop there.
      li 
        div 
          time September 10, 2013 
          p  
            | I joined 
            a(href='http://www.ColgateDischords.weebly.com') the Colgate Dischords 
            | a Cappella group.  I had the honor of building my first website for them, but more importantly, I learned invaluable leadership and teamwork skills while being a contributing member and Director of this diverse group.
      li 
        div 
          time May 1, 2014
          p After two semesters in the Computer Science program at Colgate, I was hooked.  I knew it would be my major, and I couldn't wait to learn more.  Unfortunately, after only doing it for a year, I didn't know where to start. 
      li 
        div 
          time June 1, 2014
          p My first summer of college, I was jobless.  I had very little experience in programming, but I didn't want to do anything else for the summer.  I also was too naive to realize that I didn't need a job in programming to learn more, a critically important lesson to learn. 
      li 
        div 
          time July 1, 2014
          p 
            | Thankfully, 
            a(href='http://www.modusbox.com/') ModusBox 
            | took me under their wing during my first summer job hunt and let me be their Java Development Intern.  
            | They were a young startup at the time, and almost all of the technology that we used was foreign to me at the time, but I learned as fast as possible to do what I could for the project. It was my first experience of what programming and web development could actually be like, and it was a lot of learning.  I loved it. 
      li 
        div 
          time July 1, 2015
          p 
            | A year later, I found myself teaching at 
            a(href='https://flatironschool.com/') Flatiron Schools in Boston 
            | where, as a Summer Program Assistant, I aided in the web development education of over 50 middle school and high school students. 
            | In a two week bootcamp, students would learn the basics of programming.
            | They advanced up through more complex programming, HTML and CSS lessons, all the way to a full Ruby-on-Rails application.  Being able to instill the passion for programming in my students that I saw was inspiring, and is a reminder that every day of coding should be as fun as that first "Hello World!".
      li 
        div 
          time Now 
          p Currently, I'm working full-time as a Web Application Developer at Toxikon Corporation, primarily focusing on ASP.NET MVC Development.  I'm in the process of making the change to a MEAN Stack for any applications that the stack fits.  I'm a lone developer at a 200+ person pre-clinical pharmaceutical testing company, and it is definitely a unique expereience.  I teach myself something new every day, and hope to continue that trend into the future
          
